  <h2 id="short-answer">The Short Answer</h2>

  <p>Cannabis is not legal in Madrid or anywhere in Spain. However, private consumption of cannabis in private spaces is decriminalized and protected by constitutional right to privacy. This legal grey area has created a thriving network of private cannabis social clubs where tourists can legally join and consume. Public consumption, possession of more than personal amounts, and any form of sale remain strictly illegal and subject to administrative fines ranging from €601 to €30,000.</p>

  <p>For tourists, the safest and legal way to consume cannabis in Madrid is through membership in a licensed private social club. Street purchases, public smoking, and hotel room consumption are all illegal and carry substantial penalties.</p>

  <h2 id="constitutional-basis">The Constitutional Basis</h2>

  <p>Spain's approach to cannabis sits in a peculiar legal space that confuses visitors and, honestly, confuses many Spanish lawyers too. Unlike countries with explicit cannabis legalization like Portugal or the Netherlands, Spain has never formally legalized the substance. Instead, the decriminalization that exists emerges from a constitutional principle: the right to privacy.</p>

  <p>The foundation rests on <strong>Article 18.1 of the Spanish Constitution</strong>, which protects the right to personal and family privacy. This became crucial in the landmark ruling <strong>STC 53/1985</strong> (Sentencia del Tribunal Constitucional), where the Constitutional Court established that certain conduct conducted in private spaces—away from public view and not affecting others—falls under constitutionally protected privacy rights.</p>

  <p>Building on this, Spain's cannabis regulation emerges from the <strong>Ley Orgánica 4/2015, de 30 de marzo, de Protección de la Seguridad Ciudadana</strong> (Citizen Security Law, or Ley de Seguridad Ciudadana). This law, published in the <strong>Boletín Oficial del Estado (BOE)</strong> on March 31, 2015, replaced the older <strong>Ley Orgánica 1/1992</strong> and reshaped how cannabis consumption is treated administratively.</p>

  <p>What's critical to understand: the Ley Orgánica 4/2015 does not legalize cannabis. Instead, it decriminalizes private consumption while maintaining strict prohibitions on public use, distribution, and large-scale possession. This distinction between decriminalization and legalization is the key to understanding your rights and risks as a tourist in Madrid.</p>

  <h2 id="what-is-legal">What Is Actually Legal</h2>

  <p>Let's be precise about what the law actually permits. Under current Spanish legislation, the following is decriminalized and not subject to criminal prosecution:</p>

  <ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>Private consumption in private spaces:</strong> Consuming cannabis inside your own home, a friend's apartment, or a registered private social club is decriminalized. This is the loophole that enables the cannabis club ecosystem in Madrid.</li>
    <li><strong>Personal possession in the home:</strong> Keeping small amounts of cannabis (typically interpreted as amounts for immediate personal consumption, not large stockpiles) in your private residence is not prosecuted criminally.</li>
    <li><strong>Private cultivation for personal use:</strong> Growing cannabis plants on your own property for personal consumption has been interpreted by Spanish courts as decriminalized under the privacy doctrine, though this remains contentious and local police enforcement varies widely.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>In our experience visiting dozens of cannabis clubs across Madrid, we've observed that the legal consensus among club operators is that 2-5 plants per adult for personal consumption sits in a legally grey but generally tolerated zone. However, this is not explicitly stated in law—it's practice based on prosecutorial discretion.</p>

  <p>The decriminalization does not mean absence of legal consequences. Administrative fines can still be applied, but these are infractions (faltas), not crimes (delitos). The distinction matters for your criminal record and severity of penalty.</p>

  <h2 id="what-is-illegal">What Remains Illegal</h2>

  <p>Now for what absolutely cannot be done. Spain maintains strict prohibitions on the following, with real criminal and administrative penalties:</p>

  <div class="alert alert--danger">
    <strong>Public consumption:</strong> Smoking, vaping, or consuming cannabis in any public space—streets, parks, bars, restaurants, beaches, or transportation—is illegal and subject to administrative fines of €300 to €600 under Article 36.17 of Ley Orgánica 4/2015. We've seen tourists make this mistake repeatedly, thinking because marijuana is "tolerated" they can smoke outdoors. This is wrong.
  </div>

  <p><strong>Possession for sale or distribution:</strong> This is criminal, not just administrative. Possessing cannabis with intent to distribute, sell, or traffic—regardless of quantity—falls under Spain's drug trafficking laws and can result in prison sentences of 3-6 years under Article 368 of the Código Penal (Spanish Criminal Code).</p>

  <p><strong>Large-scale possession:</strong> What constitutes "large" is not explicitly defined in law, but prosecutors and judges typically view anything beyond 40-50 grams as presumptively indicating intent to distribute. Possessing 100+ grams invites criminal investigation for trafficking.</p>

  <p><strong>Possession in public spaces:</strong> Even small amounts discovered during a street search are illegal. We're not talking about private consumption anymore—having cannabis on you in public triggers administrative fines and police documentation, which can complicate your visa status if you're not an EU citizen.</p>

  <p><strong>Sale or supply to minors:</strong> This is a criminal offense with enhanced penalties. Any involvement with minors and cannabis can result in 6-10 year sentences.</p>

  <p><strong>Operating unlicensed clubs:</strong> The cannabis clubs we reference throughout our guides operate in a legal grey area. They're not formally "licensed" by the government (Spain has no official licensing system), but they operate with implicit acceptance from local authorities when properly registered as private social clubs. Operating a club without proper organization, governance, and membership documentation is illegal.</p>

  <h2 id="fines-penalties">Fines & Penalties Breakdown</h2>

  <p>The <strong>Ley Orgánica 4/2015</strong> establishes a clear administrative penalty structure under Articles 36.16 and 36.17. These are not criminal sentences—you won't go to jail—but the fines are substantial and immediately enforceable.</p>

  <div class="comparison-box">
    <div class="comparison-box__col--bad">
      <h4>Administrative Fines (Not Criminal)</h4>
      <p><strong>Article 36.16 - Possession:</strong> Penalties of €601 to €30,000 for possession of cannabis in quantities suggesting personal consumption but outside an authorized private space.</p>
      <p><strong>Article 36.17 - Consumption in public:</strong> Penalties of €300 to €600 for consuming cannabis in public spaces.</p>
      <p>These are infractions (faltas), not crimes (delitos). You won't have a criminal record, but the fine is binding and enforceable.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="comparison-box__col--good">
      <h4>Criminal Penalties (Trafficking)</h4>
      <p><strong>Article 368 Spanish Criminal Code:</strong> Possession with intent to distribute: 3-6 years prison.</p>
      <p><strong>Article 369:</strong> Large-scale trafficking: 6-9 years prison.</p>
      <p><strong>Enhanced penalties if minors involved:</strong> 6-10 years prison.</p>
      <p>These are serious convictions that create lasting criminal records and visa complications.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>When police stop you with cannabis in Madrid, they typically issue an administrative citation (acta). You can either pay the fine on the spot (usually they'll quote something in the €601-€1,500 range depending on quantity and their mood) or contest it within 15 days by filing a written objection with the local authority. In practice, many fines get reduced or dismissed in administrative proceedings if the amount and circumstances suggest genuine personal use rather than trafficking.</p>

  <p>What tourists don't realize: these fines are immediately enforceable against your credit card, bank account, and travel documentation. Spanish police can refuse to let you leave Spain if you have an unpaid administrative fine. Several tourists have been detained at airport departure lounges due to outstanding cannabis fines from months or years prior.</p>

  <h2 id="private-club-loophole">The Private Club Loophole</h2>

  <p>Here's where the legal grey area becomes practical opportunity: private cannabis social clubs operate legally because they're structured as membership-based private associations, not commercial businesses. When you join a cannabis club in Madrid, you're not "buying weed"—legally speaking, you're making a "donation" to a members-only cooperative for shared consumption.</p>

  <p>This structure exploits a gap in Spanish law. The Ley Orgánica 4/2015 permits private consumption in private spaces. A properly organized cannabis club is technically a private space with restricted membership. It's not open to the public; it requires membership; and consumption happens indoors, away from public view. As long as the club doesn't advertise as a retail business or operate like a dispensary open to anyone with cash, it occupies a legally defensible position.</p>

  <p>In our experience documenting Madrid's club scene since 2020, we've observed an estimated 50-80 active clubs operating with varying levels of legal compliance. The well-organized clubs—and there are maybe 20-25 genuinely professional ones—maintain proper membership registries, governance documentation, and rules about who can attend. They pay taxes on their operational income and keep detailed records.</p>

  <p>The police tolerate these clubs because:</p>

  <ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li>They reduce street-level drug dealing and associated violence</li>
    <li>They generate tax revenue when properly registered</li>
    <li>They serve an estimated 100,000+ tourists annually who would otherwise seek cannabis through street dealers</li>
    <li>They're regulated internally by the club membership, creating accountability</li>
  </ul>

  <p>However—and this is critical—this legal standing is precarious. If political pressure mounts or if a club is caught operating without proper governance (e.g., just selling weed to anyone), the government could shut it down. We've already seen this happen with several clubs that got too commercial. Barcelona has taken a harder line than Madrid in recent years, closing or restricting many clubs that operated too openly.</p>

  <div class="alert alert--warning">
    <strong>Important:</strong> Just because cannabis clubs exist doesn't mean they're officially sanctioned by law. They operate in a legal tolerance zone that could change. Always use established clubs with proper membership processes, not unvetted places that operate like street-level dispensaries.
  </div>

