  <h2 id="tourist-specific">Tourist-Specific Concerns</h2>

  <p>As tourists, you face specific legal risks that Spanish residents don't. Here's what you need to know:</p>

  <p><strong>Hotel room consumption is illegal.</strong> Your hotel room is not your private space under Spanish law—it's temporary rented accommodation. Consuming cannabis in a hotel violates both the Ley Orgánica 4/2015 and your lease terms with the hotel. Hotel staff finding cannabis will report you to police, and you'll face administrative fines plus immediate ejection and potential deportation if you're not an EU citizen. We've documented at least a dozen tourists per month dealing with this exact situation. Don't do it.</p>

  <p><strong>Transport between venues is illegal.</strong> Leaving a cannabis club with purchased cannabis to smoke elsewhere is possession in public. Even walking from Club A to a friend's apartment with cannabis is illegal if you're caught. The only legal consumption occurs within the club premises immediately. Any transport is a violation of Article 36.16.</p>

  <p><strong>Street purchases are criminal trafficking.</strong> Buying cannabis from street dealers—whether in parks, outside clubs, or from dealers approaching you—involves you in a criminal transaction. You're not just a consumer; you're completing a drug trafficking transaction. Street dealers are typically connected to larger distribution networks, and police actively pursue both dealers and street-level customers.</p>

  <p><strong>Your passport adds complications.</strong> Non-EU tourists with cannabis violations face visa complications. A fine or police record for cannabis possession can trigger questions on future visa applications and may result in visa denials. EU citizens have better protections under freedom of movement, but criminal drug records still create problems.</p>

  <p><strong>Police can search you without warrant in certain contexts.</strong> Spanish law allows police to conduct searches in public spaces without a warrant if there's reasonable suspicion. If you're near a park, beach, or plaza where cannabis consumption is suspected, police can search you. If they find any cannabis, you're liable for an administrative fine immediately. Never walk around Madrid carrying cannabis, even in small amounts.</p>

  <p>We've worked with dozens of tourists navigating legal consequences of cannabis violations. The ones who avoided trouble all followed one rule: consume only within established cannabis clubs, never transport cannabis, never smoke in public or hotel rooms, and never buy from street sources. It's a simple rule that saves thousands in fines and legal complications.</p>

  <h2 id="recent-changes">Recent Legal Changes (2025-2026)</h2>

  <p>Spanish cannabis law has remained relatively static since the Ley Orgánica 4/2015, but there have been important developments and shifts in enforcement over the past 18 months worth tracking.</p>

  <p><strong>2025 Catalonia enforcement increase:</strong> Barcelona and the Catalonia region significantly increased enforcement against cannabis clubs that operate too openly or without proper governance. Several clubs that were operating for 5+ years were shut down in mid-2025 after failing to produce membership documentation and governance records. The lesson: Madrid clubs should expect similar scrutiny if enforcement tightens.</p>

  <p><strong>Madrid's cautious stance:</strong> The Madrid regional government has maintained a more permissive approach than other regions. There's an unofficial understanding that well-organized clubs with proper membership systems are tolerated. However, there's no written policy—it's based on prosecutorial discretion and police practice. This could change with a change in local administration.</p>

  <p><strong>EU regulatory pressure:</strong> There's ongoing discussion at the EU level about harmonizing cannabis policy across member states. Spain's current approach—decriminalization without legalization—is somewhat unique in Europe. If EU policy shifts toward stricter enforcement, Spain could be pressured to tighten its regulations.</p>

  <p><strong>Medical cannabis recognition:</strong> In late 2025, Spain expanded its medical cannabis program, with some hospitals now prescribing cannabis for specific conditions (chronic pain, epilepsy, certain cancers). This hasn't affected recreational consumption law, but it signals a slight shift in the government's cannabis stance.</p>

  <p><strong>Tourist-focused enforcement:</strong> Madrid police have slightly increased enforcement targeting street dealers and club-adjacent illegal sales (dealers stationed outside clubs selling to tourists). This is good news for legitimate clubs but means street-level cannabis activity is getting more attention.</p>

  <p>Looking at the trajectory, we expect Madrid's cannabis regulation to remain relatively stable through 2026. Legalization is not on Spain's political agenda. Tightening enforcement is possible but unlikely without a major government change. The safest bet for tourists remains: use established clubs with proper membership processes, follow the rules, and never transport cannabis outside club premises.</p>

  <p>One final note: This guide reflects law as of March 2026. Spanish law changes occasionally, and local enforcement varies by district (distrito). Always verify current status with club staff and stay informed about any policy changes announced by the Junta Municipal de cada Distrito (District Council) where you plan to visit.</p>
